class Solution {
    public int maxArea(int[] height) {
        int i=0;
        int j=height.length-1;
        int result=0;
        while(i<j){
            int h=Math.min(height[i],height[j]);
            int width=j-i;
            int area=h*width;
            result=Math.max(result,area);
            if(height[i]<height[j]) i++;
            else j--;
        }
        return result;
    }
}

Note:
To solve this problem, think about what determines how much water a container can hold.
The water between two lines depends on two factors: the distance between them (width) and the 
height of the shorter line, because water will spill from the shorter side. So the area is 
calculated as (right index − left index) × min(height[left], height[right]). To maximize this 
area efficiently, we start with two pointers at the extreme ends of the array because that gives the maximum possible width. 
After calculating the area, we move the pointer that has the smaller height, since the smaller height is limiting the water level. 
Moving the taller line would only reduce the width without increasing the height, so it cannot give a better area. By repeatedly
calculating the area and moving the smaller-height pointer inward, we explore better possibilities until the pointers meet, while
keeping track of the maximum area found.
